				  <div class="accordion-item" itemscope="" itemprop="mainEntity" >
					<h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
					  <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThree">
						<b itemprop="name"><span class="sr">03.</span> How does ecommerce SEO differ from standard SEO?</b>
					  </button>
					</h2>
					<div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThree" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
						<div itemscope="" itemprop="acceptedAnswer" >
					  <div class="accordion-body" itemprop="text">
						<span>
	<p>Ecommerce SEO and regular SEO share a lot of commonalities, as they both aim to optimise websites for better visibility and rankings in search engines. However, due to the specific nature of ecommerce sites, there are certain unique aspects that differentiate ecommerce SEO. Here are some of them:</p>
	<ul class="ul-circle">
		<li>
			<strong>Product descriptions:</strong> Ecommerce sites typically contain many product pages. Each of these product pages needs a unique, keyword-optimised description. This differs from regular SEO, where you might focus more on optimising informational content. Ecommerce SEO requires creating relevant, engaging, and keyword-rich descriptions for potentially hundreds or thousands of individual products. Category or collection page content is also a focus.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Product schema markup:</strong> Ecommerce SEO often involves implementing Product Schema markup. This is a type of structured data that helps search engines understand the details of the product, such as price, availability, reviews, etc. Regular SEO might use different types of Schema, depending on the nature of the website.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>User experience (UX):</strong> While UX is important in all SEO, it's particularly critical in ecommerce—if the site is hard to navigate, customers are likely to leave. UX in ecommerce includes elements like site search, filter options, clear navigation to different product categories, and a straightforward checkout process.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Customer reviews:</strong> Ecommerce SEO places a lot of emphasis on customer reviews, as they can significantly impact click-through rates (CTR) from the SERPs. Encouraging customer reviews and incorporating them into product pages can also help generate unique content for those pages, helping them rank better.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>High-intent keywords:</strong> Unlike many informational sites, ecommerce sites usually aim to rank for transactional, high-intent keywords. These are phrases that indicate the searcher is close to making a purchase, like "[product] for sale" or "buy [product]".
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Image optimisation:</strong> Ecommerce sites typically have many more images than other sites, and these images need to be optimised effectively. This includes using descriptive file names, alt text, and ensuring the image file size isn't too large, which could slow down page load times.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Managing out-of-stock products:</strong> Unlike regular websites, ecommerce sites often have to deal with discontinued or out-of-stock products. These require specific SEO strategies to either preserve the page's SEO value or correctly redirect it to a relevant, in-stock product.
		</li>
		<li>
			<strong>Security:</strong> While this is important for all websites, security is especially crucial for ecommerce sites, as they handle sensitive customer information. Having a secure (HTTPS) site is a ranking factor in Google, and it can also impact customer trust.
		</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Remember, the underlying principles of SEO remain the same, whether it's for ecommerce or a regular site—create high-quality, user-focused content, make sure your site is technically sound and easy to navigate, and earn high-quality backlinks. But the strategies used to achieve these goals can differ based on the specific requirements and challenges of ecommerce SEO.</p>
</span>
					  </div>
						</div>
					</div>
				  </div>
				  
				  
